In this project, we will start from general aspect to specific topics. Considering gender as the main orientation, and starting from that, we will go and find out different feathers in different genders, and do the estimates.

2 Basic Analysis

2.0 Data Procesing

Load the data and fill all blanks with NA. Remove the first row which is the questions of the survey. Then make two subsets based on Man and Woman.

library(dplyr)

dat = read.csv("~/Downloads/kaggle_survey_2020_responses.csv",na.strings=c("","NA"))
dat = dat[-c(1),]

male = subset(dat,dat$Q2 == "Man")
female = subset(dat,dat$Q2 == "Woman")

2.1 General Glance

Generally count the number of participants in different genders, and associate it with age, country, and level of education. And show and analyze graphically.

Gender only

gender = c("Man", "Woman", "Nonbinary", "Prefer not to say", "Prefer to self-describe")
count = rep(NULL,5)
for (j in 1:5){
  count[j] = length(which(dat$Q2 == gender[j]))
}
Gender = data.frame(Gender = gender, num = count)
barplot(Gender$num, main = "Gender", names.arg = Gender$Gender)

Gender and Age

age = sort(unique(dat$Q1), decreasing = FALSE)
num = rep(NULL,5*11)
for (i in 1:11){
  count = rep(NULL,5)
  for (j in 1:5){
    count[j] = length(which(dat$Q1 == age[i] & dat$Q2 == gender[j]))
  }
  num = c(num,count)
}

age2 = matrix(num,ncol = 11, byrow = FALSE)
colnames(age2) = age
rownames(age2) = gender

barplot(age2, main = "Gender and Age",col = c("lightblue", 'blue','darkblue','red','lightgreen'), legend = gender,beside = TRUE,las = 2)

Gender and Country

2.3 Working Experiences

In this part, we will figure out the connection between Roles and Coding experiences, and make both point and interval estimate for the fraction of students with few coding experiences. Then check if gender affects this.

# graph for the current role
Role = sort(unique(dat$Q5))
newgender = c("Man", "Woman")
num4 = rep(NULL,2*13)
for (i in 1:13){
  count = rep(NULL,5)
  for (j in 1:2){
    count[j] = length(which(dat$Q5 == Role[i] & dat$Q2 == newgender[j]))
  }
  num4 = c(num4,count)
}

Role2 = matrix(num4, ncol = 13, byrow = FALSE)
colnames(Role2) = Role
rownames(Role2) = newgender

par(cex.axis=0.55)
boxplot(Role2, main = "Current Role and Gender(Man and Woman)",col = rainbow(13),las = 2)

# Graph for coding experience
ct = sort(unique(dat$Q6))
num5 = rep(NULL,2*7)
for (i in 1:7){
  count = rep(NULL,5)
  for (j in 1:2){
    count[j] = length(which(dat$Q6 == ct[i] & dat$Q2 == newgender[j]))
  }
  num5 = c(num5,count)
}

ct2 = matrix(num5, ncol = 7, byrow = FALSE)
colnames(ct2) = ct
rownames(ct2) = newgender

par(cex.axis=0.55)
boxplot(ct2, main = "Current Coding Experience and Gender(Man and Woman)",col = rainbow(7),las = 2)

Point estimate and interval estimate

# number of students with few coding experience
n = length(which(dat$Q5 == "Student" & dat$Q6 == "< 1 years")) + length(which(dat$Q5 == "Student" & dat$Q6 == "1-2 years"))

# Estimator, SE and 95% Confidence Interval
# Among all students
xbar1 = n / length(which(dat$Q5 == "Student"))
SE1 = ((xbar1 * (1 - xbar1))^(0.5)) / (length(which(dat$Q5 == "Student")))^(0.5)
CI1 = c(xbar1 - 2 * SE1, xbar1 + 2 * SE1)
xbar1
## [1] 0.593889
SE1
## [1] 0.006829482
CI1
## [1] 0.580230 0.607548
# Among all participants
xbar2 = n / nrow(dat)
SE2 = ((xbar2 * (1 - xbar2))^(0.5)) / (nrow(dat))^(0.5)
CI2 = c(xbar2 - 2 * SE2, xbar2 + 2 * SE2)
xbar2
## [1] 0.1532741
SE2
## [1] 0.002545073
CI2
## [1] 0.1481840 0.1583643

2.4 Languages

Coding languages are the most essential parts of data work. So in this part, we will make both point and interval estimate for the average number of languages used in regular basis for new student coders.

# Counts the number of languages used 
students = subset(dat, dat$Q5 == "Student")[1:20]
students$na_count <- apply(students, 1, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
num_lan = c(13 - students$na_count)
students$num_lan = num_lan

# Estimate, SE, CI and PI( average number of known languages) 
x = students$num_lan
n = nrow(students)

Xbar = mean(x)
SEx = sd(x) / sqrt(n)
SDx = sd(x)
CIx = c(Xbar - 2 * SEx, Xbar + 2 * SEx)
PIx = c(Xbar - 2 * SDx, Xbar + 2 * SDx)
Xbar
## [1] 2.508606
CIx
## [1] 2.463063 2.554148
PIx
## [1] -0.7663349  5.7835462
# Graph
qqnorm(x)
abline(x, SEx, col = "red", lwd = 2)

hist(x)

3 Advanced Analysis

After the previous analysis we did above, there is a question: does the longer coding experience coders have, the more languages they usually use on a regular basis? Do the different coding experiences imply different numbers of languages they use? In this part, we will figure it out.

ano = students[c(7,22)]
ano = ano %>% arrange(desc(Q6))
index = which(ano$Q6 == "I have never written code")
ano = ano[-index,]
result = aov(ano$num_lan ~ ano$Q6)
summary(result)
##               Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## ano$Q6         5   1008  201.55   94.42 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   4828  10305    2.13                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 44 observations deleted due to missingness
boxplot(ano$num_lan ~ ano$Q6)
